Program: The Reith Lectures
Title: A Licence for Licence
Link: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00h192k
Last Broadcast Date: Wed 9 Dec 1987
Once an iconoclastic force, the avant-garde is now comfortably absorbed into modem society. These are the sentiments of English composer Professor Alexander Goehr in his fourth Reith Lecture entitled 'A Licence for Licence'. Speaking in his series 'The Survival of the Symphony', Professor Alexander Goehr warns of the creative death such acceptance can bring. Avant-garde is supposed to be nonconformist, modern and experimental but how can it be these things when the modern listeners find it educational and acceptable? Show less